## What this slice does
TypeScript parity for integration tracking (user task: "add this to the TS SDK").
New src/integrations/integrationMetadata.ts mirrors the Python module:
IntegrationMetadata {name, version, meta}, libraryIntegration(), asAttributes()
(nested), applyIntegrationMetadata() (non-overriding merge), asOtelAttributes()
(flattened for OTel). version defaults to packageVersion (utils/packageVersion.ts).

OpOptions gained a generic `attributes?: Record<string, any>`; op.ts seeds the
per-call attributes object from options.attributes, then layers kind/color on top
(kind/color win on collision). Integrations wired:
- op-based (openai images, anthropic create+stream, googleGenAI generate*): set
  attributes: asAttributes(<INTEGRATION>) in their OpOptions.
- openai chat/responses (direct createCall) + openai.agent + openai.realtime.agent
  (callback saveCallStart): spread ...asAttributes(<INTEGRATION>) into the dict.
- piCodingAgent (OTel spans): spread ...asOtelAttributes(...) into each startSpan's
  attributes; widened the tool span's `Record<string,string>` to
  `Record<string,string|number|boolean>` to accept the helper's scalar union.

## Precedence divergence from Python (intentional, documented)
In TS, op-level attributes flow through the per-call `attributes` arg, which is the
HIGHEST-precedence layer in WeaveClient.createCall (global < context < per-call).
So TS op-level attributes are highest, whereas Python's are lowest. For the
integration key this is immaterial (no realistic user collision). Faithfully
reproducing Python's lowest-precedence would require threading a separate op-default
channel through createCall — not worth it for this use case.

## Known limitation
meta.package_version is NOT captured in TS (only package_name). Getting the patched
library's version requires threading the version the CJS/ESM loader already reads
(utils/commonJSLoader.ts / esm/instrument.mts) through the HookFn into each
integration — deferred. Python captures it via importlib.metadata; TS sets
version=SDK version + meta.package_name only.

## Reserved-key note (pre-existing, left alone)
WeaveClient.createCall merges `{ weave: {...}, ...combinedAttributes }`, so a user
attribute could clobber the reserved `weave` block. This pre-dates my change and I
didn't touch it. attributes.integration is unaffected (separate top-level key).

